Weather Modeling with XGBRegression

The goal of this project is to develop a weather model that uses independent variablessuch as sunshine duration, daylight duration, precipitation sum, precipitation hours, month, and yearto predict the average temperature for a given day. The historical data for this project was sourced from https://open-meteo.com/ and pertains to Orem, Utah, spanning the years 2005 to 2025. At each step, I provide a summary of the objectives and explain how these contribute to building a robust and generally accurate weather model.

Below, I separate the time fields into month and year. This step will be useful for creating data visualizations. When building our models, we will also utilize the feature_importances_ function to evaluate the significance of the independent features (daylight_duration, night_duration, sunshine_duration, precipitation_sum, precipitation_hours) as well as month and year.

When feeding our data into the model, I will exclude the temperature_2m_min and temperature_2m_max columns. The goal of this project is to develop a model that uses independent variables to predict a dependent variable, temperature_2m_mean. Since temperature_2m_min and temperature_2m_max are not independent of temperature_2m_mean, they will be excluded from our set of independent variables.

Out[]:
<Axes: >

Above, we created a correlation matrix to examine the relationships between our variables and identify any high correlations that could impact our model. We define a high correlation as greater than 0.9 or less than -0.9. Upon inspection, we observe that daylight_duration and night_duration are perfectly negatively correlated, meaning these columns provide essentially the same information but with opposite effects. For example, while daylight_duration shows a strong positive correlation with mean temperature, night_duration exhibits an identical correlation but in a negative direction. In fact, the values in these columns are exact opposites. Therefore, to avoid redundancy, we will drop the night_duration column and retain daylight_duration during the pre-processing phase.

Additionally, we notice that precipitation_sum and precipitation_hours are highly positively correlated. This observation aligns with expectations, as longer durations of rainfall often result in higher precipitation totals. However, since these columns differ slightly, we will retain both to determine if one has a greater impact on our model than the other.

Data Visualization

Below, we create a single plot containing five distinct diagrams for each 5-year period, highlighting the following:

  1. Minimum, average, and maximum temperatures over the last 5 years.

  2. Monthly distributions of minimum, maximum, and average temperature densities within the 5-year period.

  3. Average day and night durations for each month over the past 5 years.

  4. Average monthly precipitation during the last 5 years

  5. Average monthly sunshine duration during the last 5 years

In[]:
fig, axes = plt.subplots(5, 4, figsize=(60,32))
sns.set_style("ticks")

def temp_plot(data, start_year, end_year, axes_index, axes_column):
  axes[axes_index, axes_column].set_ylabel("Temperature (F)")
  axes[axes_index, axes_column].set_xlabel("Time")
  axes[axes_index, axes_column].set_ylim(-20, 110)
  green_legend = mpatches.Patch(color = 'green',label='Min Temperature')
  orange_legend = mpatches.Patch(color='orange',label='Max Temperature')
  blue_legend = mpatches.Patch(color='blue',label='Mean Temperature')
  axes[axes_index, axes_column].legend(handles=[orange_legend, blue_legend, green_legend], loc='lower right')
  axes[axes_index, axes_column].set_title("Temperature from " + str(start_year) + "-" + str(end_year) + " in Orem, Utah")
  sns.scatterplot(data=data[(data['year'] >= start_year) & (data['year'] < end_year)], x='time', y='temperature_2m_min', ax=axes[axes_index, axes_column], color='green')
  sns.scatterplot(data=data[(data['year'] >= start_year) & (data['year'] < end_year)], x='time', y='temperature_2m_max', ax=axes[axes_index, axes_column], color='orange')
  sns.scatterplot(data=data[(data['year'] >= start_year) & (data['year'] < end_year)], x='time', y='temperature_2m_mean', ax=axes[axes_index, axes_column], color='blue')

def temp_density(data, start_year, end_year, axes_index, axes_column):
  axes[axes_index, axes_column].set_xlabel("Time")
  axes[axes_index, axes_column].set_ylabel("Temperature (F)")
  axes[axes_index, axes_column].set_ylim(-20, 110)
  axes[axes_index, axes_column].set_title("Temperature Densities from " + str(start_year) + "-" + str(end_year) + " in Orem, Utah")
  red_legend = mpatches.Patch(color='red', alpha=0.6, label='Max Temperature')
  blue_legend = mpatches.Patch(color='blue',label='Mean Temperature')
  green_legend = mpatches.Patch(color = 'green',label='Min Temperature')
  axes[axes_index, axes_column].legend(handles=[red_legend, blue_legend, green_legend])
  axes[axes_index, axes_column].set_xticks(range(1,13))
  axes[axes_index, axes_column].set_xticklabels(['Jan', 'Feb', 'Mar', 'Apr', 'May', 'Jun', 'Jul', 'Aug', 'Sep', 'Oct', 'Nov', 'Dec'])
  sns.violinplot(data=data[(data['year'] >= start_year) & (data['year'] < end_year)], x='month', y='temperature_2m_mean', ax=axes[axes_index, axes_column],color='blue')
  sns.violinplot(data=data[(data['year'] >= start_year) & (data['year'] < end_year)], x='month', y='temperature_2m_max', ax=axes[axes_index, axes_column], color = 'red', alpha=0.6)
  sns.violinplot(data=data[(data['year'] >= start_year) & (data['year'] < end_year)], x='month', y='temperature_2m_min', ax=axes[axes_index, axes_column], color='green', alpha=0.6)

def day_night_duration(data, start_year, end_year, axes_index, axes_column):
  filtered_data = data[(data['year'] >= start_year) & (data['year'] < end_year)]
  grouped_data = filtered_data.groupby(['month'])[['daylight_duration (h)', 'night_duration (h)']].mean().reset_index()
  dat_night = pd.melt(grouped_data, id_vars=['month'], value_vars=['daylight_duration (h)','night_duration (h)'], var_name='variable',value_name='Average')
  dat_night['month'] = dat_night['month'].astype(int)

  axes[axes_index, axes_column].bar(dat_night[dat_night['variable'] == 'daylight_duration (h)']['month'],
         dat_night[dat_night['variable'] == 'daylight_duration (h)']['Average'],
          label='Daylight', width=0.5, color="orange")
  axes[axes_index, axes_column].bar(dat_night[dat_night['variable'] == 'night_duration (h)']['month'],
         dat_night[dat_night['variable'] == 'night_duration (h)']['Average'],
          bottom=dat_night[dat_night['variable'] == 'daylight_duration (h)']['Average'],
         label='Night', width=0.5, color="mediumpurple")
  for container in axes[axes_index, axes_column].containers:
    axes[axes_index, axes_column].bar_label(container, label_type='center', color='black', fontsize=10, fmt='%.2f')

  axes[axes_index, axes_column].set_xlabel("Month")
  axes[axes_index, axes_column].set_ylabel("Duration (h)")
  axes[axes_index, axes_column].set_title("Average Day and Night Duration per Month from " + str(start_year) + "-" + str(end_year) + " in Orem, Utah")
  orange_legend = mpatches.Patch(color="orange", label="Day Duration")
  purple_legend = mpatches.Patch(color="mediumpurple", label="Night Duration")
  axes[axes_index, axes_column].legend(handles=[purple_legend, orange_legend])
  axes[axes_index, axes_column].set_xticks(range(1,13))
  axes[axes_index, axes_column].set_xticklabels(['Jan', 'Feb', 'Mar', 'Apr', 'May', 'Jun', 'Jul', 'Aug', 'Sep','Oct', 'Nov', 'Dec'])

def average_precipitation(data, start_year, end_year, axes_index, axes_column) :
  filtered_data = data[(data['year'] >= start_year) & (data['year'] < end_year)]
  grouped_data = filtered_data.groupby(['month', 'year'])[['precipitation_sum (mm)']].sum().reset_index()
  precip_data = grouped_data.groupby(['month'])[['precipitation_sum (mm)']].mean().reset_index()
  data_prec = pd.melt(precip_data, id_vars=['month'], value_vars=['precipitation_sum (mm)'], var_name='variable',value_name='Average')
  data_prec['month'] = data_prec['month'].astype(int)

  bar_plot = axes[axes_index, axes_column].bar(data_prec[data_prec['variable'] == 'precipitation_sum (mm)']['month'],
          data_prec[data_prec['variable'] == 'precipitation_sum (mm)']['Average'], width =0.5)
  axes[axes_index, axes_column].bar_label(bar_plot, label_type='center', color='black', fontsize=10, fmt='%.2f')
  axes[axes_index, axes_column].set_xticks(range(1,13))
  axes[axes_index, axes_column].set_xticklabels(['Jan', 'Feb', 'Mar', 'Apr', 'May', 'Jun', 'Jul', 'Aug', 'Sep', 'Oct', 'Nov', 'Dec'])
  axes[axes_index, axes_column].set_xlabel("Month")
  axes[axes_index, axes_column].set_ylabel("Precipitation (mm)")
  axes[axes_index, axes_column].set_title("Average Monthly Precipitation from " + str(start_year) + "-" + str(end_year) + " in Orem, Utah")

def average_sunshine(data, start_year, end_year, axes_index, axes_column):
  filtered_data = data[(data['year'] >= start_year) & (data['year'] < end_year)]
  grouped_data = filtered_data.groupby(['month', 'year'])[['sunshine_duration (h)']].sum().reset_index()
  precip_data = grouped_data.groupby(['month'])[['sunshine_duration (h)']].mean().reset_index()
  data_prec = pd.melt(precip_data, id_vars=['month'], value_vars=['sunshine_duration (h)'], var_name='variable',value_name='Average')
  data_prec['month'] = data_prec['month'].astype(int)

  bar_plot = axes[axes_index, axes_column].bar(data_prec[data_prec['variable'] == 'sunshine_duration (h)']['month'],
          data_prec[data_prec['variable'] == 'sunshine_duration (h)']['Average'], width =0.5, color = 'green')
  axes[axes_index, axes_column].bar_label(bar_plot, label_type='center', color='black', fontsize=10, fmt='%.2f')
  axes[axes_index, axes_column].set_xticks(range(1,13))
  axes[axes_index, axes_column].set_xticklabels(['Jan', 'Feb', 'Mar', 'Apr', 'May', 'Jun', 'Jul', 'Aug', 'Sep', 'Oct', 'Nov', 'Dec'])
  axes[axes_index, axes_column].set_xlabel("Month")
  axes[axes_index, axes_column].set_ylabel("Sunshine Duration (h)")
  axes[axes_index, axes_column].set_title("Average Monthly Sunshine Duration from " + str(start_year) + "-" + str(end_year) + " in Orem, Utah")

In the diagram above, I present five distinct plots for each 5-year period.

  • The first row of plots displays the maximum, average, and minimum temperatures over time. A quick glance reveals that minimum temperatures have increased, indicating that winter months are generally becoming warmer as time goes on.

  • The second row depicts temperature densities by month for each 5-year period. Similarly, this row suggests winter months are increasing in temperature over time. Additionally, summer months exhibit less variation in temperatures, while the rest of the year shows wider ranges in maximum, average, and minimum temperatures.

  • The third row highlights the average day and night durations by month across each 5-year period. This row suggests that day and night durations remain largely consistent over the years.

  • The fourth row illustrates the average monthly precipitation sum (mm). As expected, winter months generally experience higher precipitation levels than summer months. Notably, July or August consistently shows the lowest average precipitation sum for each 5-year period.

  • The final row showcases the average monthly sunshine duration across each 5-year period, which remains mostly consistent throughout the years.

Data Pre-Processing and Standardization

In this section, we will pre-process our data. Using the describe function below, we observe that there are no missing values, which is ideal. As discussed earlier, we will drop the night_duration column. We will also encode the categorical data and standardize the numerical data. This is necessary because we do not want the year column (ranging from 2005 to 2025) to outweigh other columns such as sunshine_duration or precipitation_sum. While sunshine_duration has a greater impact on temperature than the year column, failing to standardize the data could cause our model to assign excessive weight to the year column. This would reduce the accuracy of our model, so it is crucial to standardize and encode the data properly before feeding it into the model.

Below, we use the StandardScaler function from the sklearn library to standardize the temperature_2m_mean, daylight_duration, sunshine_duration, precipitation_sum and precipitation_hours columns. Afterward, we concatenate the encoded month and year columns with our standardized dataset. Finally, we proceed to create our training and testing datasets.

In[]:

standardized = pd.concat([standardized_data, data[['month', 'year']]], axis=1)
standardized['time'] = data['time']

Creating the Train, Validation and Test Data Sets

Below, we construct training, testing, and validation datasets to evaluate our model's performance. The training dataset will be used to train the model, while the validation dataset will assess how the model responds to unseen data. Finally, we will input the testing dataset to measure how accurately the model predicts temperature_2m_mean values. In the following sections, we will create several diagrams to visualize and showcase the model's accuracy.

XGBRegression Model

Below, we import the XGBRegression model and fit it to our training data. We set n_estimators to 5,000, learning_rate to 0.001, and early_stopping_rounds to 50. This configuration instructs the model to build up to 5,000 base regression models while using the root mean square error (RMSE) to evaluate the performance of each model. The early_stopping_rounds parameter halts the training process if the model's performance on the validation set does not improve after 50 consecutive rounds.

After fitting the model to the training set, we print the RMSE for both the training and validation sets. The model halts training after 3,395 rounds, indicating that the RMSE plateaus at 0.37549. Notably, the RMSE on the validation set decreases from 0.96620 to 0.37549, which is ideal. This demonstrates that the model effectively learns to predict the temperature_2m_mean over the course of 3,395 base models.

Out[]:
<Axes: xlabel='temperature_2m_mean', ylabel='XGB predictions'>

In the diagram above, we plot temperature_2m_mean against the predicted temperature_2m_mean generated by our XGBRegression model. Ideally, the points would align perfectly along the y = x line, indicating that the model has accurately predicted the temperature_2m_mean values. However, as shown in the graph, deviations from this line reveal instances where the model either underestimates or overestimates the temperature_2m_mean values.

Despite these deviations, the graph generally follows the y = x trend line, suggesting that the model performs reasonably well in predicting temperature_2m_mean. Notably, there is greater dispersion around the y = x line in the lower-left corner compared to the upper-right corner. This indicates that the model struggles more with predicting lower temperatures (negative numbers) than higher temperatures (positive numbers).

xgb_regression_importances = regression.feature_importances_
xgb_reg_feature_importances = pd.DataFrame({'Feature': x_train_set.columns, 'Importance' : xgb_regression_importances})
xgb_reg_feature_importances = xgb_reg_feature_importances.sort_values(by='Importance')
plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
sns.barplot(data=xgb_reg_feature_importances, x='Feature', y='Importance')
plt.title('Feature Importance for XGBRegression Model')
plt.xlabel('Features')
plt.ylabel('Importance')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.tight_layout()

Above, we plot the feature_importances_ for our XGBRegression model. Clearly, our regression model weights sunshine_duration (h), month and daylight_duration (h) more than precipitation_hours (h), year or precipitation_sum (mm). This makes sense, as weather would be dependent on the month of the year, the sunshine_duration and daylight_duration of each day/month throughout that year. This diagram is also saying that precipitation_sum, precipitation_hours and year are not weighted heavily when predicting what the temperature_2m_mean is on a given day.

Conclusion

After extensive exploratory data analysis, pre-processing, and standardization, we successfully developed a weather model that takes in variables such as precipitation_sum (mm), precipitation_hours (h), daylight_duration (h), sunshine_duration (h), month, and year to predict the average temperature for a given day. While the model is not without its flaws, it effectively captures the seasonality present in the dataset and can generally predict the weather for a specific day. Weather forecasting is inherently complex, but by leveraging historical data, we gain valuable insights into how each independent variable influences the predicted average temperature.
